I have increased Republican chances since last time. Shapiro is spending a lot of money and Mastriano almost zero, but the polls are within the margin or error. Shapiro needs to do more than talk about Mastriano's vulnerabilities and liabilities (which are enormous) and more than the one positive issue he has raised-his appropriate prosecution of abusive priests. He has made the point and continued focus on that risks alienating the Catholic faithful who have positive feelings toward their clergy, while acknowledging prior misdeeds. There is lots to talk about-the economy, energy, education, infrastructure, an extraction tax for fracking and Shapiro's superior qualifications.

The real question in this race is, how messy will the Republican Primary be? There are about a dozen declared candidates with almost about another two dozen expressing interest or looking at the possibility. Of course, the field will be culled to a much smaller number, but still with four or more candidates and no clear favorite, Republicans could do a lot of damage to each other before getting to the general election. The Democrats seems to be consolidating around the AG. The advantage goes to the Republican for the moment because of demographics of the state and the historical trends, but a lot is still developing.

There is almost a switch in party after a 2 term governor in PA. Off-year elections hurt the party in power, though governors often have greater ticket-splitting, Shapiro could benefit from a fractured field, though the fundamentals will be hard to overcome.

The polling numbers on the ground seems to suggest a flip, but a lot could happen this year. Tradition says that a Republican will be elected Governor of Pennsylvania this year, but this almost certainly be a close race all the way to the end regardless of the party nominees.

Seems like it favors going R. 4 governorships typically lost by president's party, and this one will have no incumbency advantage for D's, in a state Biden won by only 1.2%. https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/a-very-early-look-at-the-2022-governor-races/

Since 1971, the Pennsylvania Governorship has entered a near perfect 2 term cycle alternating between Democrat (D) and Republican (R) - 1971-1979 = D = 2 Term 1979-1987 = R = 2 Term 1987-1995 = D = 2 Term 1995-2003 = R = 2 Term 2003-2011 = D = 2 Term 2011-2015 = R = 1 Term (The Republican Governor Was Uniquely Unpopular) 2015-2023 = D = 2 Term

Democrats have historically been elected to two terms in PA vs Republicans who typically only get one term. However, the incumbent, Tom Wolf, is on his way out in 2023 and with the incumbent out, the historical norm is for the opposing party to take over (in PA).
